<h2>The 17.1 KB target is unverified</h2>
<p>
  The card&rsquo;s &ldquo;~17.1 KB compact target&rdquo; appears <strong>nowhere in the repo</strong> — only in
  the card body, sourced from a compaction hook firing during #1864. The sole <em>documented</em> harness limit
  is ~24.4 KB silent truncation (<code>check-memory.mjs:7</code>), which the 22 KB gate already clears. So
  <strong>Fork 1</strong> keeps tracking the documented limit and dismisses the phantom (skeptic:
  <strong>SURVIVES</strong>).
</p>

<h2>The crux: does the harness recall unindexed files?</h2>
<p>
  <code>docs/agent/memory-management.md:57</code> says topic files &ldquo;need not have an index line at all
  once the index is at budget,&rdquo; but the gate <strong>errors</strong> on unindexed files calling them
  &ldquo;unreachable by recall context&rdquo; (<code>check-memory.mjs:90-91</code>) — a direct policy↔gate
  contradiction. The whole mechanism decision (<strong>Fork 2</strong>) pivots on one fact only the running
  harness can settle: <em>is an unindexed fact file recalled by its <code>description</code>?</em> If
  <strong>yes</strong> → evict lowest-recall entries to recall-only files + relax the gate (real load
  reduction). If <strong>no</strong> → eviction is deletion-with-extra-steps; instead delete the aspirational
  <code>:57</code> line, accept a bounded index, and reduce load via rule 1 (right-home invariants to
  <code>platform-decisions.md</code>). Sharding is rejected both ways (the harness auto-loads
  <code>MEMORY.md</code> only).
</p>

<h2>Skeptic</h2>
<p>
  Fork 2 was <strong>REFUTED</strong> as first drafted (the &ldquo;build a lazy tier&rdquo; default presumed a
  recall mechanism the repo can&rsquo;t show), so it is reframed: the empirical recall check is the unlock and
  the policy-clarification branch is the safe default. Full grounding in
  <code>reports/2026-06-27-always-loaded-memory-index-tiering.md</code>.
</p>
